<div class="project-docs">

  <p class="docs-note">// RU version: <a class="docs-link" href="https://github.com/nikitak-dev/nikitak-dev.github.io/blob/main/src/components/docs/folder-clone.ru.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">folder-clone.ru.md</a></p>
  <p class="docs-note">// UA version: <a class="docs-link" href="https://github.com/nikitak-dev/nikitak-dev.github.io/blob/main/src/components/docs/folder-clone.ua.md" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">folder-clone.ua.md</a></p>

  <section class="docs-block">
    <h3 class="docs-heading">// WHAT IT DOES</h3>
    <p>Hands you a complete, faithful copy of a Drive folder -- every nested level intact, nothing flattened or left behind -- sitting in its own clearly named workspace, ready to hand off.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-block">
    <h3 class="docs-heading">// HOW IT WORKS</h3>
    <p>You give it a folder link and a name; it spins up a dated target folder and walks the source from the top down, recreating each subfolder and copying its files in batches as it goes. When the tree is done, it drops a report into the new folder -- total files and folders, broken down by type -- and messages you that the copy is ready.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="docs-block">
    <h3 class="docs-heading">// GOOD TO KNOW</h3>
    <p>A backend automation kicked off from a short form -- nothing to try here. It copies into the operator's own Drive and stamps each new folder with the client name and date, so repeat runs never collide.</p>
  </section>

</div>
